<methodology slug="frameworks">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Eight pre-revenue research frameworks routed to match the current decision: ideation, niche evaluation, validation, JTBD, TAM/SAM/SOM, competition, and Value Proposition Canvas.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>research-frameworks</tag>
      <tag>product-market-fit</tag>
      <tag>niche-evaluation</tag>
      <tag>ideas</tag>
      <tag>sizing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Research Frameworks: A Router for Pre-Revenue Decisions</title>

    <summary>A toolbox of eight named pre-revenue research frameworks — 7Ps ideation, Paul Graham questions, niche evaluation (50-point matrix), validation criteria, Jobs-to-be-Done, TAM/SAM/SOM, competitive intelligence, and Value Proposition Canvas — treated as a router: the agent picks the smallest subset that answers the current decision, not all eight at once.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Framework theater — producing a 50/50 niche score with zero primary research — is worse than no score. The router approach forces the agent to justify which frameworks are relevant, locks the ICP in one sentence before any framework runs, and requires a URL + retrieval date on every external number. Downstream SDD agents (faion-sdd) ingest the artifacts directly.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Founder at the "what should I build?" stage needing a structured idea funnel.</item>
        <item>Investor pitch requiring TAM/SAM/SOM plus a competitive table.</item>
        <item>Pivot review: re-score current niche against the same matrix to make stay/pivot defensible.</item>
        <item>GTM repositioning: rebuild the Value Proposition Canvas before rewriting the homepage.</item>
        <item>Multi-idea triage: score N ideas in parallel and rank by niche score.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Already shipping with paying customers — use cohort analysis and retention curves instead.</item>
        <item>Single-question clarifications ("should I charge $19 or $29?") — use a pricing experiment.</item>
        <item>Pure technical scoping (architecture, API design) — use SDD design.md.</item>
        <item>Hobby projects, internal tools, OSS side projects with no revenue goal.</item>
        <item>Two-sided marketplaces pre-launch where supply/demand dynamics dominate.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="router-logic">
      <title>Router Logic: Picking the Right Framework Subset</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pick the smallest subset of frameworks that answers the current decision — never run all eight at once. Decision modes: idea, validate, size, position, pivot.</statement>
        <rationale>Running all eight frameworks on one idea is framework theater. Agents default to exhaustive execution; the router constraint prevents this and keeps output actionable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>idea mode: 7Ps + Paul Graham questions + niche evaluation</item>
        <item>validate mode: validation criteria + JTBD + problem interviews</item>
        <item>size mode: TAM/SAM/SOM + competitor analysis</item>
        <item>position mode: Value Proposition Canvas + competitor analysis + JTBD</item>
        <item>pivot mode: niche evaluation + TAM/SAM/SOM + Value Proposition Canvas</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Lock the ICP in one sentence before any framework runs; reuse that sentence verbatim across all artifacts.</statement>
        <rationale>Frameworks produce inconsistent outputs when each run re-infers a slightly different ICP. One locked sentence prevents drift and enables downstream SDD agents to ingest artifacts directly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="artifact-pipeline">
      <title>Artifact Pipeline (Idea to Spec)</title>
      <list>
        <item>1. Discovery: apply 7Ps + Paul Graham in parallel; output idea-candidates.md (10-20 raw ideas)</item>
        <item>2. Triage: score each candidate on the 50-point niche matrix; cull anything below 30</item>
        <item>3. Validation: pick top 3, run validation criteria with primary research (5+ interviews, Google Trends, Reddit)</item>
        <item>4. Jobs: write JTBD statements (functional + emotional + social) for the survivor</item>
        <item>5. Sizing: TAM/SAM/SOM via three-method triangulation; flag spread > 2x; do not average</item>
        <item>6. Competition: fill 6-dimension table (features, pricing, positioning, tech, feedback, GTM)</item>
        <item>7. Positioning: Value Proposition Canvas; check pain-relievers cover top-3 pains</item>
        <item>8. Handoff: write executive-summary.md linking all artifacts; pass to faion-sdd for spec.md</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="7ps-ideation">
      <title>7Ps of Ideation</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Apply all 7 Ps systematically, generate 2-3 ideas per P, and tag each idea with its underlying user-pain-id to prevent duplication across Pain/Profession/People cells.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents fill Pain/Profession/People with restatements of the same idea. Requiring a unique user-pain-id per idea forces structural diversity across the seven prompts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Pain: What frustrates you (or your target user) daily? Focus on problems you personally understand.</item>
        <item>Passion: What do you love doing? Look for intersection with a market need.</item>
        <item>Profession: What is broken in your industry? Look for manual, error-prone, or expensive processes.</item>
        <item>Process: What workflow is inefficient? Code review, billing, scheduling, onboarding.</item>
        <item>Platform: What can be improved on an existing platform? Better Slack integrations, Notion plugins, VS Code extensions.</item>
        <item>People: Who do you know with problems? Freelancers, founders, ops teams, developers.</item>
        <item>Product: What product do you wish existed? What do you hack together repeatedly?</item>
      </list>
      <example type="good" title="Intersection of multiple Ps">
        <note>Pain (meeting coordination is broken) + Passion (developer tooling) + Platform (VS Code) = async standup bot for distributed engineering teams.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="paul-graham-questions">
      <title>Paul Graham Questions</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For agent runs, skip "What do you find yourself building for yourself?" — agents cannot honestly answer this and will invent a project. Use the other three questions and pipe in real user history if available.</statement>
        <rationale>Paul Graham questions reward introspection, not aggregation. LLMs trained on generic startup content will produce plausible but fabricated answers to introspective prompts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>What is tedious but necessary? Look for manual, repetitive tasks that users accept as unavoidable.</item>
        <item>What is surprisingly hard to do? Tasks that seem simple but require expert knowledge or coordination.</item>
        <item>What would you pay for that does not exist? Unmet needs with demonstrated willingness to pay.</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Validate each Paul Graham answer with 2-3 other people before treating it as a market signal, and check whether solutions already exist.</statement>
        <rationale>Personal pain points are necessary but not sufficient for a market. A solution that already exists at reasonable cost means the problem is solved, not an opportunity.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="niche-evaluation-matrix">
      <title>Niche Evaluation Matrix (50 points)</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Score each of five criteria 1-10, require a one-line justification AND a cited source URL for market-size and competition columns before accepting the score.</statement>
        <rationale>A 50/50 niche score with zero primary research is worse than no score — it legitimizes guesses. Citations force the agent to ground numbers in real evidence.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Market size (25%): 1-3 = &lt;$10M, 4-6 = $10-100M, 7-10 = >$100M</item>
        <item>Competition (20%): 1-3 = red ocean (saturated), 4-6 = moderate, 7-10 = blue ocean (new)</item>
        <item>Barriers to entry (20%): 1-3 = high (capital, regulatory), 4-6 = medium, 7-10 = low (can start tomorrow)</item>
        <item>Profitability (20%): 1-3 = thin margins (&lt;10%), 4-6 = OK (10-30%), 7-10 = high (>30%)</item>
        <item>Personal fit (15%): 1-3 = no relevant skills, 4-6 = some skills, 7-10 = perfect match</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>40-50 points: excellent opportunity, pursue immediately</item>
        <item>30-39 points: good potential, worth testing</item>
        <item>20-29 points: proceed with caution, consider pivots</item>
        <item>&lt;20 points: consider other ideas or major pivots</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="validation-criteria">
      <title>Validation Criteria: Five Tests for Market Signal</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Apply all five validation criteria (frequency, intensity, WTP, search volume, competition) before recommending pursuit; the presence of competitors is a green flag, not a red flag — it confirms the problem exists.</statement>
        <rationale>No competitors usually means no market, not a blue ocean. Absence of search volume means people are not actively looking for a solution. Both are failure signals.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Frequency: must be weekly or more — "How often do you face this?" Monthly or less fails.</item>
        <item>Intensity: 7+ out of 10 — "How painful is this (1-10)?" Below 7 rarely creates urgency to pay.</item>
        <item>Willingness to pay: must be yes — "Would you pay to solve this?" and a dollar figure, not just yes/no.</item>
        <item>Search volume: must exist — Google Trends, keyword volume. People looking for solutions confirms demand.</item>
        <item>Competition: must exist — someone trying to solve it validates the problem; gaps in existing solutions are the opportunity.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="jobs-to-be-done">
      <title>Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD) with Measurability Rules</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Write the functional JTBD statement first using the "When/I want/So I can" template with a verifiable outcome — reject any outcome phrased as an adjective ("feel empowered") and replace with a measurable verb ("invoice sent in &lt;90s, paid within 14 days").</statement>
        <rationale>JTBD statements drift into wishful copywriting when outcomes are unmeasurable. Verifiable outcomes anchor product decisions and can be tested in user research.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Functional JTBD with measurable outcome">
        <note>When I finish client work, I want to quickly generate and send professional invoices, so I can get paid within 14 days without a follow-up call.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Wishful JTBD with unmeasurable outcome">
        <note>When I finish client work, I want to feel professional and empowered, so I can build my reputation. — no measurable outcome, cannot be tested.</note>
      </example>
      <list>
        <item>Functional jobs: what tasks are they trying to accomplish? ("Send invoice to client")</item>
        <item>Emotional jobs: how do they want to feel? Derive from functional, do not invent. ("Feel confident the payment will arrive")</item>
        <item>Social jobs: how do they want to be perceived? Derive from functional. ("Be seen as reliable by clients")</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tam-sam-som">
      <title>TAM/SAM/SOM Market Sizing with Three-Method Triangulation</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Triangulate market size with three methods (top-down, bottom-up, competitor-based); do not average if the spread is greater than 2x — report the range and flag the divergence instead.</statement>
        <rationale>Averaging incompatible methods produces false precision. A 2x spread signals that one method's assumptions are wrong; averaging hides the problem and misleads investors.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Top-down: TAM = total industry size from reports; SAM = TAM * % matching our criteria; SOM = SAM * realistic capture rate</item>
        <item>Bottom-up: TAM = # potential customers * average revenue per customer; SAM = # reachable customers * ARPU; SOM = # we can acquire * ARPU</item>
        <item>Value theory: TAM = value created by solving the problem; SAM = value for specific segment; SOM = value we can capture</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Round aggressively — $8.3B is fake precision, $8B is honest. Use two significant figures maximum for TAM/SAM.</statement>
        <rationale>Market sizing compounds errors across four multipliers. Reporting four significant figures implies an accuracy that the underlying data does not support.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="competitive-intelligence">
      <title>Competitive Intelligence Table</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap competitor analysis at 5-7 named direct players plus one explicit "long tail" row; tag the rest as "long tail" with an estimated count.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents over-list adjacent products to appear thorough. A table of 20 competitors is less useful than a tight table of 6 with deeper analysis per row.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Features: what do they offer? what is missing? — source: product pages, demos, reviews</item>
        <item>Pricing: how much? what tiers? — source: pricing pages, sales calls, G2</item>
        <item>Positioning: who do they target? what message? — source: homepage, ads, case studies</item>
        <item>Technology: what stack? what integrations? — source: job postings, BuiltWith, tech blogs</item>
        <item>Customer feedback: what do users love/hate? — source: G2/Capterra reviews, support forums</item>
        <item>GTM strategy: how do they acquire customers? — source: SimilarWeb traffic, Meta Ad Library, Ahrefs</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="value-proposition-canvas">
      <title>Value Proposition Canvas with Evidence-Based Fit Check</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Check VPC fit against actual user quotes (cite interview ID per row), not assumed pains/gains — agents over-claim fit when both sides of the canvas are invented.</statement>
        <rationale>A VPC always "fits" if the agent invented both customer profile and value map. Requiring interview citations per pain-reliever and gain-creator row forces the canvas to be grounded in evidence.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Customer profile (right): customer jobs (functional/emotional/social), pains (obstacles, risks, bad outcomes), gains (desires, success criteria)</item>
        <item>Value map (left): products and services offered, pain relievers (how you eliminate pains), gain creators (how you create gains)</item>
        <item>Fit check: do pain-relievers address top-3 pains? do gain-creators fulfill top-3 desired gains? does offering help with important jobs?</item>
      </list>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Declaring VPC "fit" without checking pain-relievers against top-3 pains from actual interviews.</description>
        <reason>VPC fit is always partial in reality. Over-claiming fit before launch leads to underinvestment in validation and a false sense of readiness.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="citation-rules">
      <title>Citation Requirements and Anti-Hallucination</title>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cite a URL with retrieval date on every external number. LLM-only cells are explicitly tagged "estimate".</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs hallucinate framework cells fluently. Without a citation requirement the niche matrix becomes confidently wrong. The "estimate" tag signals which numbers need validation before acting on them.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Require two independent scorers (or two agent runs) for niche scoring; average only if within 2 points on each criterion.</statement>
        <rationale>Identical inputs to two agent runs produce 15+ point spread. Two runs with averaged scores are more reliable than one run treated as ground truth.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <title>AI Agent Gotchas and Failure Modes</title>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinate framework cells fluently; without a citation requirement the niche matrix becomes confidently wrong.</description>
        <reason>Require citations; with a citation requirement the niche matrix becomes confidently wrong becomes grounds for rejection. The "estimate" tag signals which numbers need validation before acting on them.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Confirmation bias: if the user hints "this should be a $1B market" or "I love this idea", the agent reverse-engineers high scores.</description>
        <reason>Pre-commit the scoring rubric before showing the hypothesis.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>7Ps duplication: the agent fills Pain/Profession/People with restatements of the same idea.</description>
        <reason>Tag each idea with the underlying user-pain-id to enforce non-overlap.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Paul Graham introspection prompts ("what do you find yourself building?") force the agent to invent a personal project.</description>
        <reason>Skip these for agent runs or pipe in real user history.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Niche scoring drift: identical inputs to two agent runs produce 15+ point spread.</description>
        <reason>Fix random seed or require a justification per cell to reduce variance.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>JTBD wishful copywriting: "feel empowered" is not measurable; LLMs default to adjectives.</description>
        <reason>Require a verifiable outcome ("invoice sent in &lt;90s, paid within 14 days").</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Stale training data: the model "knows" 2023 market sizes and 2022 competitor lists.</description>
        <reason>Force fresh web fetches for anything post-cutoff.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Currency mixing: agents mix USD/EUR/GBP within one TAM report.</description>
        <reason>Normalize to USD with a dated FX rate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>VPC over-fit: the canvas always "fits" if the agent invented both sides.</description>
        <reason>Require pains/gains sourced from interviews and pain-relievers from the spec.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Competitive table over-listing: agents add every adjacent product to appear thorough.</description>
        <reason>Cap to direct + 1 indirect tier and tag the rest as "long tail".</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <title>Best Practices for Framework Use</title>
      <list>
        <item>Pick a subset, not the whole toolbox — running all eight frameworks on one idea is framework theatre.</item>
        <item>Lock the ICP in one sentence before any framework runs; reuse that sentence verbatim across artifacts.</item>
        <item>Cite a URL with retrieval date on every external number; LLM-only cells are explicitly tagged "estimate".</item>
        <item>Niche scoring: require a one-line justification per criterion and force two independent scorers (or two agent runs) — average only if within 2 points.</item>
        <item>TAM/SAM/SOM: triangulate three methods (see sibling methodology); never average if spread > 2x.</item>
        <item>JTBD: write the functional statement first; emotional/social are derivative. Replace adjectives with verbs.</item>
        <item>Validation: 5+ user interviews beats any framework; the matrix is a checklist, not a substitute.</item>
        <item>VPC fit must be checked against actual user quotes, not assumed pains/gains; cite the interview ID per row.</item>
        <item>Competitor table: cap at 5-7 named players plus an explicit "long tail" row — agents tend to over-list.</item>
        <item>Round aggressively: $8.3B is fake precision, $8B is honest; two sig figs max for TAM/SAM.</item>
        <item>Re-score every 6 months; diff the assumptions, not the headlines.</item>
        <item>Frameworks output artifacts in .aidocs/product_docs/; downstream agents read these — keep filenames stable.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <title>Framework Limitations and Failure Modes</title>
      <list>
        <item>Framework theatre: producing a 50/50 niche score with zero primary research is worse than no score. The matrix legitimizes guesses.</item>
        <item>7Ps overlap heavily — Pain/Profession/People all collapse into "user X has problem Y". Agents tend to duplicate ideas across cells.</item>
        <item>Paul Graham questions reward introspection, not aggregation; LLMs cannot honestly answer "what do you find yourself building for yourself?" — they will invent a project.</item>
        <item>Niche scoring's 1-10 scale is anchored by whoever scores first; two agents on the same idea diverge by 15+ points.</item>
        <item>TAM/SAM/SOM compounds error across four multipliers — see market-research-tam-sam-som methodology for the divergence-flag pattern.</item>
        <item>JTBD statements drift into wishful copywriting ("…so I can feel empowered") instead of measurable outcomes.</item>
        <item>Competitive intelligence is biased toward funded/visible competitors; the long tail is invisible to agents.</item>
        <item>VPC fit-check ("do gain creators fulfill desired gains?") is binary in the canvas but always partial in reality — agents over-claim fit.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/framework-router.sh" purpose="Shell router: prints relevant framework names for a given decision mode (idea|validate|size|position|pivot)."/>
    </templates>

